liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Home affairs minister Clare O'Neil spoke after Minister Rishworth, discussing the need for a migration strategy to help with skills shortages, and it is designed to complement the measures in the White Paper. "When we arrived in government we found a migration system fundamentally open which had no real strategy behind, a system not oriented towards our national challenges and complex, expensive and slow," she said. "It was also a system where the high skilled workers that we need to help lift of Australian workers were having the most difficulty is coming to the country and yet we were seeing large amounts of migration of people aggregating and lower paid sectors where they are highly vulnerable to exploitation, a migration that had it backwards. "There is a really important process at the heart of the White Paper that is being released today and that the Treasurer has run and that is making a clear statement that we will not follow what were 10 years of policy malaise that preceded our Government. "Instead we intend to tackle the challenges and capture these opportunities by pulling every lever within our power and that's why the work Treasurer has led here is so important, the migration strategy which will be the first time our country has ever had a strategy defining our migration system will be released in the coming weeks, we see this as twin products that we are going to use every lever of national power to make sure we drive productivity growth so that Australians can get higher wages and better jobs."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Home affairs minister foreshadows the release of the migration review strategy

spoke after Minister
Rishworth, discussing the need for a migration strategy to help with skills shortages, and it is designed to complement the measures in the White Paper.

"When we arrived in government we found a migration system fundamentally open which had no real strategy behind, a system not oriented towards our national challenges and complex, expensive and slow," she said.

"It was also a system where the high skilled workers that we need to help lift of Australian workers were having the most difficulty is coming to the country and yet we were seeing large amounts of migration of people aggregating and lower paid sectors where they are highly vulnerable to exploitation, a migration that had it backwards.

"There is a really important process at the heart of the White Paper that is being released today and that the Treasurer has run and that is making a clear statement that we will not follow what were 10 years of policy malaise that preceded our Government.

"Instead we intend to tackle the challenges and capture these opportunities by pulling every lever within our power and that's why the work Treasurer has led here is so important, the migration strategy which will be the first time our country has ever had a strategy defining our migration system will be released in the coming weeks, we see this as twin products that we are going to use every lever of national power to make sure we drive productivity growth so that Australians can get higher wages and better jobs."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Minister Rishworth continues, saying the government is also removing a disincentive for people on income support: "The second measure we are announcing today is an extension of what is called the nil rate for those on income support. "What this means is we are removing the disincentive that sometimes might happen because a person might get offered some short-term work, but as a result may fear the loss of concessions, including their concession card, and access to childcare subsidies, and indeed worried that if the work does not work out, they will have to reapply for JobSeeker. "So what this extension will do it will allow someone to take up may be short-term work and still remain part of the income support system, allowing a smoother transition, to allow a person to take up short-term work and not feel there is a disincentive if that work does not continue. "We know that there is already for example three months in the system that allows you to do this, but we heard through our consultation, this is not long enough, so today the government is announcing we will be extending that period to six months, which will allow some security for people to take up the opportunity of short-term work and not worry about the impact that that will have."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: JobSeekers can work for six months before it affects concession payments
